<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>What is the difference between linkable assets and regular content?</strong></p>
<p>Regular content serves your audience. Linkable assets serve people who create content for your audience. Assets are designed to be cited and referenced.</p>
<p><strong>How long does it take for a linkable asset to earn backlinks?</strong></p>
<p>With active promotion, first links appear within 2-4 weeks. Consistent passive citations build over 6-12 months. Original research reports might see 10-40 links in the first 90 days.</p>
<p><strong>Which type of linkable asset earns the most links?</strong></p>
<p>Interactive tools and original research reports typically earn the most links. Tools provide ongoing utility. Research provides unique data. Both give writers reasons to cite.</p>
<p><strong>Do I need original data to create a linkable asset?</strong></p>
<p>No. Curated statistics pages, definitive guides, and resource hubs do not require original research. However, original data typically earns more links because it is unique.</p>
<p><strong>How often should I update linkable assets?</strong></p>
<p>Update statistics pages quarterly. Update research reports annually. Update tool lists quarterly. Update pricing comparisons monthly. Dynamic trackers should update continuously.</p>
<p><strong>Can small businesses create linkable assets?</strong></p>
<p>Yes. Small businesses can create templates, checklists, curated statistics pages, and expert roundups with minimal investment. Original research requires more resources but is not mandatory.</p>
<p><strong>How do I promote a linkable asset?</strong></p>
<p>Share with your email list and social followers. Outreach to industry bloggers and journalists. Share in relevant communities. Monitor for unlinked mentions and request links. Pitch to journalists covering related topics.</p>
